.pl 62
                            Chapter 3


                         DSI-32 PROGRAMS


3.1  INTRODUCTION

DSI-32  assembly  language programs and how the DSI-32  Assembler 
assigns memory addresses to symbols,  instruction,  and data  are 
covered in this Chapter.


3.2  DSI-32 MODULE STRUCTURE

A  DSI-32  program  may  be  divided  into  separately  assembled 
modules.  A  module consists of one or more segments and has  the 
following form:

  [MODULE <symbol>]
   <segment-1>
   <segment-2>
      .
      .
      .
   <segment-n>

description:

   MODULE <symbol>  is  the  optional  MODULE  pseudo-op.  If  it 
                    appears  within  the  current  module   being 
                    assembled  the string <symbol> is written  to 
                    the object file as the module name, otherwise 
                    the  name  of the source file is assigned  as 
                    the module name.  Section 5.8.1 describes the 
                    MODULE pseudo-op in detail.

   <segment-1>      specify the segments within the module.  Each 
     thru           segment may consist of one or more  Assembler 
   <segment-n>      statements. Section 3.3 describes segments in 
                    detail.

If a program is made up several modules,  the modules must all be 
separately  assembled  and then linked together (via  the  DSI-32 
linker).
.pa
3.3  PROGRAM SEGMENTS

A  program  segment is made up of a set of statements  which  all 
have  the same relocation mode.  The following segment types  are 
supported:

   - Program Code
   - Static Base
   - Frame Pointer
   - Stack Pointer
   - Absolute
   - Immediate

3.3.1  Relocatable Addresses And Relocation Modes

Each  byte  of  data storage defined in a module  is  assigned  a 
relocatable address. A relocatable memory address is an offset to 
the  start  of the segment in which the instruction or  data  was 
defined.

Also associated with a relocatable memory address is a relocation 
mode. The relocation mode specifies the base address to which the 
address is relative.  The Assembler assigns a relocation mode  to 
an  instruction  or  data element depending on the  type  of  the 
segment in which it is defined or whether the relocation mode was 
explicitly  defined.  Table  3-1 lists the  permitted  relocation 
modes:
.cw 10

                      TABLE 3-1  RELOCATION MODES

-------------------------------------------------------------------------
|   Name  |	Mode type	|	Description			|
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
|    PC   |	Program code	| Value is relative to the start of the |
|	  |			| program code segment			|
|	  |			|					|
|    SB   |	Static Base	| Value is relative to the SB register  |
|	  |			| at run time.				|
|	  |			|					|
|    FP   |	Frame Pointer	| Value is relative to the FP register	|
|	  |			| at run time.				|
|	  |			|					|
|    SP   |	Stack Pointer	| Value is relative to the SP register	|
|	  |			| at run time.				|
|	  |			|					|
|    AB   |	Absolute	| Value is the absolute memory address.	|
|	  |			|					|
|    IM   |	Immediate	| Value is a constant.			|
-------------------------------------------------------------------------
.cw 12
.pa
3.3.2  Program Code Segments

Relocation Mode - PC Relative.

It is the only segment where code generation is allowed,  all the 
constants  and  program code are generated in this  segment.  The 
location  counter  is incremented by the  appropriate  number  of 
bytes  after each statement.  The pseudo location counter may not 
be decremented in the PC segment.  The program code segments  are 
relocated  at  run  time via the Module table  mechanism  of  the 
NS32000 series of microprocessors.

3.3.3  Static Base Segments

Relocation Mode - SB Relative.

Static  data  is referenced relative to the SB  segment.  The  SB 
segment  is fixed as long as the program resides in  one  module. 
The  SB  register  is loaded from the Module table  each  time  a 
program enters a new module.

The  Assembler  pseudo  location counter is  incremented  by  the 
appropriate  amount after each instruction.  The location counter 
may not be decremented in the SB segment.

Only  uninitialized  storage may be allocated in the  SB  segment 
when using the NSX compatible DSI-32 assembler. The extended DSI-
32  assembler  allows initialized storage which is output to  the 
object file along with the code segments.

The static base segments are relocated at run time via the Module 
table mechanism of the NS32000 series of microprocessors.

3.3.4  Frame Pointer Relative

Relocation Mode - FP Relative Segment.

 - This  segment allocates storage for data items that are  local 
to  a  procedure.   Storage of FP relative data is allocated  and 
deallocated at run time.

 - FP  relative data items are allocated on the stack,  thus  the 
location  counter  is  decremented by the appropriate  number  of 
bytes.  If a label is specified on a line which allocates storage 
on  the stack,  it is assigned the value of the location  counter 
after it has been decremented by the appropriate number of bytes.

 - FP segments are on the stack and transient, thus Assembly time 
initialization is not possible.
.pa
3.3.5  Stack Pointer Relative Segment

Relocation Mode - SP Relative

Data  that is relative to the stack is allocated by this segment. 
SP relative data items are allocated on the push down stack, thus 
the location counter is decremented by the appropriate number  of 
bytes.  If a label is specified on a line which allocates storage 
on  the  stack it is assigned the value of the  location  counter 
after it has been decremented by the appropriate number of bytes.

SP  segments  like  FP and SB segments only contain  storage  for 
data,  thus Assembly time initialization is not  possible.  Again 
note  that  the extended DSI-32 assembler  allows  assembly  time 
initialized SB segments.

An  SP relative segment is relocated at run time by  instructions 
which modify the stack pointer

3.3.6  Absolute Segment

Relocation Mode - Absolute.

This segment allocates storage at absolute memory locations.  The 
absolute  location  counter  is incremented  by  the  appropriate 
number of bytes.

This  segment  is  not relocatable since it  refers  to  absolute 
addresses.   Input/output ports can be easily reference via  this 
addressing mode.

3.3.7  Immediate Segments

Relocation Mode - Immediate.

Storage  is not allocated by this segment.  The immediate segment 
is a mechanism for assigning immediate values to labels which may 
then  be  used as offsets in the various  addressing  modes.  The 
Immediate  location  counter is incremented  by  the  appropriate 
number of bytes.

This  segment is not relocatable since it doesn't refer to memory 
locations.

3.4  NESTED SEGMENTS

The  Assembler supports the nesting of segments,  i.e.  it allows 
defining a new segment within the current segment.   The  maximum 
nesting level is 16.   Note that the PC and SB segments even when 
nested  continue to increment from the last used value unlike the 
FP and SP segments which are reset on every new occurrence.

